<font color="#FF0000">THE GREAT CANADIAN RUN</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jul  8 20:08:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
When all is said and done, in the American experience Vietnam was little more than a meat grinder.  All of the young men who died, all of the wounded, physically and emotionally, all of the families destroyed, were sacrificed because Robert MacNamara didn't have courage to tell the truth.  He knew that President Johnson didn't want to hear that it was a lost cause, and he knew it was a lost cause.  Had he done what he was supposed to do, give his boss the benefit of his knowledge, experience and education, thousands of us would have been spared an experience I liken to that of German Jews during WW2.  <br><br>
If you chose not to participate in the most brutally pointless, disgracefully inept, criminally psychotic and dehumanizing  events in American history (and that's saying something), then all I can say is:  You were right.  <br><br>
If your choice involved a family, then that contains its own trips, both joyous and guilt-ridden.  They are what you deserve.  <br><br>
If your choice involved the possibility of relinquishing your citizenship, however, then you took an enormous risk.  A risk that I was unable to take.  It is with you that I would be interested in chatting: about your experience, maybe a little of mine.  <br><br>
I was unable to consider giving up what little I had here for the promise of nothing elsewhere.  And so I made my choice, and went off to kill Commies for Bob and Lyndon and later, Nixon.  But there was never an amnesty for us.  We had to live with the choice we made and there was no Jimmy Carter to say, &quot;It's OK.  Come Home.&quot;  Our choice was never reversed.  <br><br>
If you left and came home, please drop me a line.
